Redesigns the moment from Finish through arriving on Workout Complete,
previously an instant, abrupt cut (tap Finish -> screen replaced in the
same render). Expands the earlier Workout Complete screen work into the
full completion-experience redesign requested — this is the first of
that expanded plan's phases, not a continuation of the old numbering.

- Finish button now gives its own brief 'confirming' state (dimmed fill,
  checkmark, disabled) instead of firing the screen swap in the same
  instant as the tap. Enforced as a floor via Promise.all against the
  real save (FINISH_ANTICIPATION_MS = 350ms, same shared-constant pattern
  as PR_CELEBRATION_VISIBLE_MS) rather than a fixed pre-save delay, so a
  near-instant IndexedDB write can't produce a too-brief flash and a
  slower one doesn't add perceived latency beyond the intentional beat.
- Skips the anticipation entirely when there's nothing to save
  (sessionHasData false) — that path opens the discard-confirmation
  dialog instead of actually finishing, so there's nothing to anticipate.
- Handles the save-error path explicitly: onFinish resolves (doSaveWorkout
  catches internally, doesn't rethrow) but the component stays mounted, so
  a mountedRef guard resets the button after the error dialog rather than
  leaving Finish stuck disabled.
- The swap into Workout Complete is now a 300ms fade+rise entrance
  instead of an instant appearance, using the same real-state-plus-CSS-
  transition technique WorkoutHUD's PR celebration already uses — no
  animation library, nothing keyframe-based.

onFinish's prop type widened to (save: boolean) => void | Promise<void>
to match what it actually is (handleFinish is async) — a typing fix, not
a behavior change; LiveSession's own onFinish usage (Cancel) is
unaffected and still fire-and-forget.

Verified via tsc/eslint against a clean main baseline — no new errors
introduced; confirmed no incidental reformatting of unrelated code in
_app.workout.tsx leaked into the diff.
